Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.580 --> 00:00:10.290
-Well, welcome back
to the second half.

00:00:10.290 --> 00:00:14.360
We've gone from a cosmic
scale to gigalight

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:16.950
year scale, and
massive black holes,

00:00:16.950 --> 00:00:19.210
and now we're sort of
zeroing in on things

00:00:19.210 --> 00:00:22.650
that are closer
to life on Earth,

00:00:22.650 --> 00:00:24.590
and things like star formation.

00:00:24.590 --> 00:00:27.360
So the next speaker
is Blakesley Burkhart,

00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:33.030
who got her PhD from the
University of Wisconsin in 2014

00:00:33.030 --> 00:00:38.240
and does work on-- she's a
Fellow in the Submillimeter

00:00:38.240 --> 00:00:41.950
Array Collaboration, and also
a fellow, an Einstein Fellow,

00:00:41.950 --> 00:00:44.430
in the Institute for
Theory and Computation

00:00:44.430 --> 00:00:46.330
at the Center for Astrophysics.

00:00:46.330 --> 00:00:48.760
And she's going to talk
about star formation, which

00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:52.390
is actually something
that, as a dilettante,

00:00:52.390 --> 00:00:54.410
am very interested to hear.

00:00:54.410 --> 00:00:57.260
So her talk is-- title
of her talk is "Galaxies

00:00:57.260 --> 00:01:00.210
as Star Forming
Engines: Simulating

00:01:00.210 --> 00:01:01.930
the Turbulent Birth of Stars."

00:01:01.930 --> 00:01:04.310
And I remind you to
hold your questions

00:01:04.310 --> 00:01:06.157
until after the
second speaker goes,

00:01:06.157 --> 00:01:07.865
and then we'll have
a panel up here where

00:01:07.865 --> 00:01:08.990
you can ask your questions.

00:01:08.990 --> 00:01:09.864
OK, Blakesley.

00:01:15.660 --> 00:01:16.550
-So, yeah.

00:01:16.550 --> 00:01:20.422
I'm extremely happy to
be talking a little bit

00:01:20.422 --> 00:01:22.380
about my research to you
today, and to give you

00:01:22.380 --> 00:01:24.900
some impressions on
what I've figured out.

00:01:24.900 --> 00:01:31.060
In this four panel series,
I must represent purgatory.

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:34.500
So Cora and Salvatore are
representing the heavens,

00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:37.160
now we're moving
down, and so clearly,

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:41.320
the scales of the galaxies,
we've now reached purgatory.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:45.570
So Sarah, you have a
big task ahead of you.

00:01:45.570 --> 00:01:49.900
And I want to leave
you with the feeling

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:54.040
that the 21st century physics
that we're getting into,

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:57.450
galaxies represent
a huge enigma still.

00:01:57.450 --> 00:02:00.770
We still don't know things
like how a star is formed,

00:02:00.770 --> 00:02:04.440
or how galaxies
evolve in cosmic time.

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:06.650
And so today I'll
be telling you more

00:02:06.650 --> 00:02:09.460
on the lines of how
stars are forming

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:11.250
and some new progress
that we've made

00:02:11.250 --> 00:02:13.957
in terms of simulations
and comparisons

00:02:13.957 --> 00:02:15.415
with state of the
art observations.

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:22.970
So I'd like to take a step
back and start with a classic.

00:02:22.970 --> 00:02:24.920
Right, we gotta go
back to the classics,

00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:26.730
and that's Carl Sagan.

00:02:26.730 --> 00:02:29.800
Probably many of you
at least watched Cosmos

00:02:29.800 --> 00:02:32.920
or heard of the Cosmos
program, the original one.

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:35.820
Carl Sagan was the one to
say, first, that we're all

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:37.650
made of star stuff.

00:02:37.650 --> 00:02:38.990
What did he mean by that?

00:02:38.990 --> 00:02:42.820
Well, going back to what Cora
was talking about with the Big

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:47.070
Bang, the Big Bang produced
hydrogen, helium, lithium,

00:02:47.070 --> 00:02:49.570
and where did all the other
heavy elements come from?

00:02:49.570 --> 00:02:53.090
Where did the carbon, nitrogen,
oxygen, all the heavy elements

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:55.620
that make up most of the
world that we interact with

00:02:55.620 --> 00:02:57.000
and indeed our own bodies?

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.240
All of this was
synthesized within stars.

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:02.470
And so without
generations of stars

00:03:02.470 --> 00:03:05.570
that came before our own star,
before our own solar system,

00:03:05.570 --> 00:03:07.390
we would not be here today.

00:03:07.390 --> 00:03:09.990
And so then it's a big
question about the nature

00:03:09.990 --> 00:03:14.510
of our existence to ask
how do galaxies make stars.

00:03:14.510 --> 00:03:17.580
We know stars are
predominately made in galaxies,

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:18.690
how does this work?

00:03:18.690 --> 00:03:21.680
It's important for
us to find this out.

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:25.590
And so we can take a
picture of a typical galaxy.

00:03:25.590 --> 00:03:29.860
This is one of many billions of
galaxies that we've observed.

00:03:29.860 --> 00:03:32.040
And we can ask
about how they get

00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:35.560
gas, how they get gas in order
to make this gas and the stars.

00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:38.330
So first, we know that galaxies
don't exist in isolation.

00:03:38.330 --> 00:03:40.910
This galaxy here is
actually part of a network

00:03:40.910 --> 00:03:42.850
of galaxies in the cosmos.

00:03:42.850 --> 00:03:47.490
Gas accretes onto this
galaxy through a cosmic flow.

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:48.970
And then what
happens to this gas?

00:03:48.970 --> 00:03:51.490
How does galaxy turn
this gas into stars?

00:03:51.490 --> 00:03:53.620
There's a whole
cycle that this gas,

00:03:53.620 --> 00:03:56.540
once it falls onto the
galaxy, goes through

00:03:56.540 --> 00:03:58.580
in order to become a star.

00:03:58.580 --> 00:04:01.940
So we can start with this
gas being very warm and hot.

00:04:01.940 --> 00:04:04.110
It sits sort of
outside the galaxy.

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:07.500
And it cools via number of
different cooling processes

00:04:07.500 --> 00:04:09.530
into colder and denser gas.

00:04:09.530 --> 00:04:12.200
Eventually, this cold
gas becomes dense enough

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:14.860
to start to collapse under
its own gravity, which

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:16.399
we call self gravity.

00:04:16.399 --> 00:04:19.130
And then forms these
very dense clouds,

00:04:19.130 --> 00:04:21.600
sort of sitting in the
disc of the galaxy,

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:23.170
that we call molecular clouds.

00:04:23.170 --> 00:04:25.000
They're dense enough,
they're cold enough

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:28.270
that they're able to start
sustaining molecules.

00:04:28.270 --> 00:04:32.000
And then at some point, we have
this process of star formation.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.830
So you know, if you just think
of gravitational collapse,

00:04:34.830 --> 00:04:37.930
if you continue to
collapse your cloud, poof.

00:04:37.930 --> 00:04:41.820
Eventually you should collapse
it so much that a star forms.

00:04:41.820 --> 00:04:44.730
We don't actually know so
much about that process.

00:04:44.730 --> 00:04:46.660
But OK, once you
have a star, then

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:47.990
you can have solar systems.

00:04:47.990 --> 00:04:50.080
You can have stellar evolution.

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:54.350
And eventually the star will
either disrupt its parent cloud

00:04:54.350 --> 00:04:57.210
through its own winds
or feedback processes,

00:04:57.210 --> 00:05:00.000
or eventually it will
explode as a supernova.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.050
And then this
cycle then repeats.

00:05:03.050 --> 00:05:05.290
OK, easy, right?

00:05:05.290 --> 00:05:08.220
We also have in
the galaxy, again,

00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:09.770
it's not an isolated system.

00:05:09.770 --> 00:05:14.080
There is still outflows that
are returning this hot material

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:16.860
back to the
intergalactic medium.

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:20.680
This part here you could
say is one big bottleneck.

00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:23.820
We still really
have no idea how we

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:26.650
go from the formation
of clouds, how

00:05:26.650 --> 00:05:28.610
this cloud forms into a star.

00:05:28.610 --> 00:05:31.050
This is still a big mystery.

00:05:31.050 --> 00:05:34.970
But we do have some
evidence, from observations,

00:05:34.970 --> 00:05:37.980
in particular, that
clouds are forming in what

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:40.750
we call dense molecular clouds.

00:05:40.750 --> 00:05:44.770
These are just a few
images, very famous images

00:05:44.770 --> 00:05:46.900
from the Hubble Space Telescope.

00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:48.660
A lot of these
images were produced

00:05:48.660 --> 00:05:51.810
in the 1990s, when
I was growing up,

00:05:51.810 --> 00:05:54.260
and I would say images
like these really got

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:56.610
me excited to be an astronomer.

00:05:56.610 --> 00:05:59.910
These sort of images just made
me want to study astronomy.

00:05:59.910 --> 00:06:02.355
Because we just-- there's so
much variety of structure,

00:06:02.355 --> 00:06:04.550
and that you can see here,
there's so much physics

00:06:04.550 --> 00:06:06.040
going on.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:09.730
For example, in this one
here, you can see a bow shock.

00:06:09.730 --> 00:06:12.740
This is a triangle
shape here is a bow

00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:15.880
shock that's being ejected
from a young forming star.

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:18.500
All of this diffused
light material

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:20.990
here is actually
ionizing radiation

00:06:20.990 --> 00:06:22.780
from young, forming stars.

00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:25.680
And then these dense
filamentary structures

00:06:25.680 --> 00:06:28.160
are still the dense,
colder gas where stars

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:29.110
can continue to form.

00:06:29.110 --> 00:06:30.560
So there's a lot
of physics going

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:33.470
on here that we can already
see in the observations.

00:06:33.470 --> 00:06:36.520
We still don't
understand it very well.

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:38.420
But we can start to
speculate, how would you

00:06:38.420 --> 00:06:40.990
take these big clouds and
then collapse them down

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:41.670
to form a star?

00:06:41.670 --> 00:06:44.770
Well, gravity's probably
a good start, right?

00:06:44.770 --> 00:06:46.690
So you can come up
with a cartoon picture

00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:50.830
of star formation, starting
with your dense cold molecular

00:06:50.830 --> 00:06:51.950
cloud.

00:06:51.950 --> 00:06:54.960
Then you have some sort of
gravitational collapse, that's

00:06:54.960 --> 00:06:58.800
radial, the cloud collapses in
on itself towards the center.

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:00.860
At some point you
reach densities

00:07:00.860 --> 00:07:04.670
that are high enough in order
to ignite nuclear fusion.

00:07:04.670 --> 00:07:08.290
That's what a star is, right,
so we now have fusion going on.

00:07:08.290 --> 00:07:11.010
There's some outflows, there's
still an accretion disc

00:07:11.010 --> 00:07:13.550
from this original material.

00:07:13.550 --> 00:07:17.710
And eventually you start to
form planets, and a disc,

00:07:17.710 --> 00:07:18.920
and so forth.

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:20.640
So this looks
pretty good, right?

00:07:20.640 --> 00:07:25.870
I mean, this cartoon, I
feel pretty good about this.

00:07:25.870 --> 00:07:29.100
But unfortunately,
the theorists had

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:33.690
to come and ruin it for everyone
with just a simple calculation.

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:35.370
So I'll walk you through this.

00:07:35.370 --> 00:07:38.130
So we can write
down the time scale

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:41.060
it would take for a cloud
of some density to collapse.

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:42.600
This is called the
free fall time.

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:44.790
The free fall time is
really just a function

00:07:44.790 --> 00:07:47.410
of the cloud density,
assuming that the cloud is

00:07:47.410 --> 00:07:50.450
a spherical cloud, like
I showed in my cartoon.

00:07:50.450 --> 00:07:53.100
So for some typical
densities of these clouds,

00:07:53.100 --> 00:07:55.780
we can calculate a time
scale for collapse.

00:07:55.780 --> 00:07:58.690
This is something
like 8 million years.

00:07:58.690 --> 00:08:01.520
Now then I can say,
well, I know roughly

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:03.720
how much gas is in the galaxy.

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:07.160
If I look out into the galaxy,
I look with the Hubble Space

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:08.990
Telescope, with
other telescopes,

00:08:08.990 --> 00:08:10.815
I can calculate the
gas in the galaxy,

00:08:10.815 --> 00:08:14.450
and in particular, the dense
gas mass in the galaxy.

00:08:14.450 --> 00:08:17.670
Because we know stars form
in dense molecular clouds.

00:08:17.670 --> 00:08:21.560
And I can estimate a mass in
our own Milky Way galaxy of star

00:08:21.560 --> 00:08:22.450
forming gas.

00:08:22.450 --> 00:08:25.160
So that I can just say,
well, I want to find out

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:26.520
the star formation rate, right.

00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:30.930
I can just divide the mass of
the molecular gas in the galaxy

00:08:30.930 --> 00:08:35.110
by the collapse time, in order
to get a rate of conversion

00:08:35.110 --> 00:08:37.880
of gas into stars.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:40.520
So if I do that, I
get a expected rate

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:44.660
of around 250 solar
masses per year.

00:08:44.660 --> 00:08:47.420
Now, what do we
actually observe?

00:08:47.420 --> 00:08:50.420
This is what my theoretical
calculation would predict.

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:52.970
The actual observed star
formation rate in the Milky

00:08:52.970 --> 00:08:55.170
Way, is significantly lower.

00:08:55.170 --> 00:08:58.610
Something like three
solar masses per year.

00:08:58.610 --> 00:09:00.330
This is a big problem, right?

00:09:00.330 --> 00:09:02.750
We have a big,
theoretical mismatch

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:06.770
between what the theorists
that are studying star

00:09:06.770 --> 00:09:08.750
formation and the observers.

00:09:08.750 --> 00:09:13.210
And so something seems to be
slowing star formation down.

00:09:13.210 --> 00:09:15.470
So we really have an issue here.

00:09:15.470 --> 00:09:18.070
So how are we going
to solve this?

00:09:18.070 --> 00:09:20.610
So really, the problem
of star formation

00:09:20.610 --> 00:09:22.640
is not how we form stars, right.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:24.860
We know gravity eventually
wants to bring everything

00:09:24.860 --> 00:09:26.760
together and form
a star, but really

00:09:26.760 --> 00:09:29.880
the problem of star formation
is how do you not form stars?

00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:32.620
How do you get such an
inefficient star formation

00:09:32.620 --> 00:09:34.980
in our galaxy?

00:09:34.980 --> 00:09:38.970
Well, it turns out the galaxy
is actually a complicated place

00:09:38.970 --> 00:09:39.730
to live in, right.

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:41.630
There's a lot of
physics going on here.

00:09:41.630 --> 00:09:43.860
This is why galaxies are
so fascinating to study,

00:09:43.860 --> 00:09:46.890
is because there's so
much going on here.

00:09:46.890 --> 00:09:50.270
In this galaxy here in this
picture, you've got dust.

00:09:50.270 --> 00:09:52.320
You can see these
dark dust slings

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:54.550
that are obscuring
the stellar light.

00:09:54.550 --> 00:09:58.720
Stars that are producing all
this bright blobs of light.

00:09:58.720 --> 00:10:00.980
You have supernovae
that are exploding,

00:10:00.980 --> 00:10:04.960
that are creating extremely
bright areas within the galaxy,

00:10:04.960 --> 00:10:07.130
brighter than the
rest of the stars

00:10:07.130 --> 00:10:09.280
all combined, of
course planets that

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:11.190
are around the stars
and then other,

00:10:11.190 --> 00:10:14.520
more exotic physical phenomena
that you've maybe heard about,

00:10:14.520 --> 00:10:16.510
like cosmic rays.

00:10:16.510 --> 00:10:19.250
Right, so, high energy
particles that are produced

00:10:19.250 --> 00:10:22.370
by things like black holes and
supernova, or magnetic fields

00:10:22.370 --> 00:10:24.784
of turbulence, which I'm going
to touch on in this talk.

00:10:24.784 --> 00:10:26.950
So there's a lot of different
physics going on here.

00:10:26.950 --> 00:10:28.250
It's very complicated.

00:10:28.250 --> 00:10:30.960
So we can easily see how
in my cartoon picture,

00:10:30.960 --> 00:10:32.240
maybe we missed something.

00:10:32.240 --> 00:10:34.710
Maybe we weren't
thinking about something.

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:37.960
Another complication,
unfortunately,

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:41.470
is that a lot of the time scales
of galaxy evolution of star

00:10:41.470 --> 00:10:45.380
formation are much, much longer
than our own human lifetimes.

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:47.690
So I showed you
the free fall time,

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:49.170
that's the fastest
that you're ever

00:10:49.170 --> 00:10:51.090
going to get one of
these clouds to collapse.

00:10:51.090 --> 00:10:54.110
It's still millions
of year time scales.

00:10:54.110 --> 00:10:57.220
And so human life times,
unfortunately, are not so long.

00:10:57.220 --> 00:11:00.670
So how are we going
to make progress here?

00:11:00.670 --> 00:11:03.530
Well, I'd like to propose
to you that we really

00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:07.120
should make progress in part
with numerical simulations.

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:10.880
So these are simulations that
are done on a computer, where

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:13.810
we take some known
physics like gravity,

00:11:13.810 --> 00:11:16.330
like the way fluid
motions work, et cetera,

00:11:16.330 --> 00:11:20.220
and then evolve them in space
and time using computers

00:11:20.220 --> 00:11:22.180
in order to study
star formation.

00:11:22.180 --> 00:11:25.450
I'm showing you a movie here,
and I want to start it over.

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:27.660
So we start with some
initial conditions.

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:30.110
So in this case it's
a spherical cloud,

00:11:30.110 --> 00:11:32.250
very similar to my
cartoon picture.

00:11:32.250 --> 00:11:34.260
And then we allow this
cloud to collapse,

00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:36.630
and we also include
other physics

00:11:36.630 --> 00:11:39.570
that we think are important
in star forming regions,

00:11:39.570 --> 00:11:43.280
like turbulence and gravity
and magnetic fields.

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:45.170
We then evolve this is time.

00:11:45.170 --> 00:11:49.190
Now you'll notice that
time is running here.

00:11:49.190 --> 00:11:52.620
This, you're getting
a density image here

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:56.360
as it zooms in to the
collapsing region in the cloud,

00:11:56.360 --> 00:12:00.070
because there's so many orders
of magnitude and spatial scale

00:12:00.070 --> 00:12:02.550
and also in density,
this color bar

00:12:02.550 --> 00:12:04.010
here, which is a long scale.

00:12:04.010 --> 00:12:07.670
So these are factors of
10, has to also zoom in.

00:12:07.670 --> 00:12:09.590
So another part
of the difficulty

00:12:09.590 --> 00:12:11.090
of the star formation
problem is not

00:12:11.090 --> 00:12:12.660
just the time scales involved.

00:12:12.660 --> 00:12:18.190
It's also the extreme range
of scales, ranges of density.

00:12:18.190 --> 00:12:21.330
So finally, we get down into
the kind of densities where

00:12:21.330 --> 00:12:23.150
the star formation
can actually happen,

00:12:23.150 --> 00:12:25.110
and then you can see
in the simulation

00:12:25.110 --> 00:12:27.070
these star particles
are starting

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:29.850
to form in the simulation.

00:12:29.850 --> 00:12:31.350
So this is a very
difficult problem.

00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:34.740
But simulations can
help us understand it.

00:12:34.740 --> 00:12:37.290
OK, so if you're going
to make a simulation,

00:12:37.290 --> 00:12:38.840
right, you need a cookbook.

00:12:38.840 --> 00:12:40.240
You need a recipe.

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:41.850
It's up to you,
you can decide what

00:12:41.850 --> 00:12:43.990
you include in your simulation.

00:12:43.990 --> 00:12:47.290
Well, what kind of recipe
would you come up with?

00:12:47.290 --> 00:12:50.094
So obviously, we
need gravity, right.

00:12:50.094 --> 00:12:52.010
So gravity's going to
pull everything together

00:12:52.010 --> 00:12:53.130
into collapse.

00:12:53.130 --> 00:12:57.310
And the movie I'm showing you
here is one such simulation

00:12:57.310 --> 00:13:00.690
that I've been working with
with the Enzo Collaboration.

00:13:00.690 --> 00:13:02.610
So you can see that
these filaments form

00:13:02.610 --> 00:13:04.930
at the start of the
simulation, and then

00:13:04.930 --> 00:13:07.460
begin to collapse
in on themselves.

00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:09.730
So pick your favorite
part of the filament,

00:13:09.730 --> 00:13:11.790
and you can follow
it in and see how

00:13:11.790 --> 00:13:15.850
it's sort of pancaking together
as the simulation proceeds.

00:13:15.850 --> 00:13:17.130
So we need gravity.

00:13:17.130 --> 00:13:21.200
What other things would you
include in your simulation

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:22.010
of star formation?

00:13:22.010 --> 00:13:23.950
How about turbulence?

00:13:23.950 --> 00:13:29.100
So if you look at this initial
gas density distribution,

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:30.510
it's very fractal.

00:13:30.510 --> 00:13:33.320
It's very non smooth.

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:35.610
There's a lot of
discontinuities there.

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:37.190
This is what we
mean by turbulence.

00:13:37.190 --> 00:13:40.080
And so, for the most part,
when we talk about turbulence

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:43.180
in our everyday lives, it's
usually an uncomfortable moment

00:13:43.180 --> 00:13:46.872
on the airplane when the captain
comes on the PA, and says,

00:13:46.872 --> 00:13:48.830
you know, we're going to
experience turbulence.

00:13:48.830 --> 00:13:52.060
And you start bumping all around
and you wish it would stop.

00:13:52.060 --> 00:13:55.030
So this is random fluid motions.

00:13:55.030 --> 00:13:57.570
When we encounter
this in the airplane,

00:13:57.570 --> 00:14:01.010
this makes the airplane, of
course, bump up and down.

00:14:01.010 --> 00:14:03.010
This is a very nice
picture by da Vinci

00:14:03.010 --> 00:14:05.540
showing a turbulent flow.

00:14:05.540 --> 00:14:07.600
And a very similar
sort of thing is

00:14:07.600 --> 00:14:09.620
happening in a molecular cloud.

00:14:09.620 --> 00:14:13.940
When we measure velocities
in these star forming clouds,

00:14:13.940 --> 00:14:17.330
we see that the velocities
are characteristic

00:14:17.330 --> 00:14:20.170
of a turbulent flow, not
a flow that's very smooth.

00:14:20.170 --> 00:14:22.800
And so you wouldn't want to
fly an airplane through one

00:14:22.800 --> 00:14:25.260
of these molecular
clouds, I can tell you.

00:14:25.260 --> 00:14:27.370
Now what does
turbulence do for us?

00:14:27.370 --> 00:14:32.400
Why do I want to put it in my
simulation of star formation?

00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:36.040
Well turbulence adds a
pressure term, right.

00:14:36.040 --> 00:14:37.590
So does anyone drink coffee?

00:14:37.590 --> 00:14:40.000
Does anyone like
French press coffee?

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.960
OK, when you stir the coffee
around in your French press,

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:46.230
you don't immediately
push it down, right.

00:14:46.230 --> 00:14:49.360
You need to wait, you need
to let it settle down.

00:14:49.360 --> 00:14:50.230
Try it.

00:14:50.230 --> 00:14:52.070
Next time you want to
drink a French press,

00:14:52.070 --> 00:14:55.990
stir the grinds around a lot,
and then try to push it down.

00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:59.690
It's very, very difficult.
You've induced turbulence

00:14:59.690 --> 00:15:01.920
into the fluid,
and that turbulence

00:15:01.920 --> 00:15:04.150
is providing an
additional pressure

00:15:04.150 --> 00:15:05.930
term that's making
it harder for you

00:15:05.930 --> 00:15:07.700
to push your French press down.

00:15:07.700 --> 00:15:09.409
So in some sense,
that's a similar thing

00:15:09.409 --> 00:15:10.450
to what's happening here.

00:15:10.450 --> 00:15:12.820
The turbulent
motions in the cloud

00:15:12.820 --> 00:15:15.420
are resisting the
gravitational collapse,

00:15:15.420 --> 00:15:17.940
and it's not able to
push the cloud in.

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:20.450
That's the main thing turbulence
is doing in the cloud.

00:15:20.450 --> 00:15:22.380
It's also doing some
other things, especially

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:23.930
on the small scales.

00:15:23.930 --> 00:15:27.795
It's actually allowing small
scales to collapse even easier.

00:15:27.795 --> 00:15:30.660
But for the most part, you're
adding a pressure term,

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:32.930
so that's going to slow
star formation down.

00:15:32.930 --> 00:15:34.860
Right, so ultimately
we want to figure out

00:15:34.860 --> 00:15:37.240
how can we slow
star formation down

00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:41.190
in order to match that three
solar mass per year number

00:15:41.190 --> 00:15:43.220
that we've sort of
observed in the Milky Way.

00:15:43.220 --> 00:15:45.390
So turbulence will slow us down.

00:15:45.390 --> 00:15:47.020
What else?

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:48.050
Magnetic fields.

00:15:48.050 --> 00:15:49.900
I bet you wouldn't've
thought that.

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:53.800
But these clouds are
actually magnetized,

00:15:53.800 --> 00:15:56.860
and that means that we
have an additional pressure

00:15:56.860 --> 00:15:58.970
term from the
magnetic field that

00:15:58.970 --> 00:16:03.130
can also resist the collapse
and slow down the clouds.

00:16:03.130 --> 00:16:07.010
Now the funny thing is that
when you talk to astrophysicists

00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:09.250
and you mention the
words turbulence,

00:16:09.250 --> 00:16:11.630
and magnetic
fields, usually they

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:13.530
run away from you very quickly.

00:16:13.530 --> 00:16:15.950
And that's because these
things are very complicated.

00:16:15.950 --> 00:16:18.260
There's no full
theory of turbulence

00:16:18.260 --> 00:16:20.510
from a fluid dynamics
standpoint of view,

00:16:20.510 --> 00:16:22.510
this is one of the
unsolved problems.

00:16:22.510 --> 00:16:27.970
And magnetic fields in a moving,
fluid plasma are also ugly.

00:16:27.970 --> 00:16:31.070
But we can also think of
some intuitive pictures

00:16:31.070 --> 00:16:32.940
to understand why
magnetic fields might be

00:16:32.940 --> 00:16:34.640
important for star formation.

00:16:34.640 --> 00:16:37.400
So for example, another
real life scenario.

00:16:37.400 --> 00:16:39.480
Think about a
rubber band, right.

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:41.500
So if you stretch
out a rubber band,

00:16:41.500 --> 00:16:43.680
a rubber band provides some
kind of tension, right.

00:16:43.680 --> 00:16:46.430
It wants to stretch back down.

00:16:46.430 --> 00:16:49.700
But with your rubber band,
which is like the magnetic field

00:16:49.700 --> 00:16:53.390
lines, you can't really
move perpendicular to them.

00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:56.190
You can only move things
parallel to your rubber band,

00:16:56.190 --> 00:16:56.690
right.

00:16:56.690 --> 00:17:00.310
So if I take something like
this, something stretchy

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:03.440
and rubbery, I can't
move my hand this way.

00:17:03.440 --> 00:17:05.750
I can only move
my hand this way.

00:17:05.750 --> 00:17:08.250
And so this is very similar
to what the magnetic field is

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:10.604
doing in a star forming cloud.

00:17:10.604 --> 00:17:11.770
So here's a picture of that.

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:14.630
You have your spherical cloud,
and you have the red lines

00:17:14.630 --> 00:17:18.020
here, being representing
the magnetic field lines.

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:23.680
So the collapse is going to
only be able to proceed parallel

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:24.839
to the field lines.

00:17:24.839 --> 00:17:26.670
The field lines
are going to resist

00:17:26.670 --> 00:17:29.820
the collapse perpendicular,
such that you will eventually

00:17:29.820 --> 00:17:32.720
arrive at a situation
where you have the collapse

00:17:32.720 --> 00:17:36.330
parallel to the field, and the
field being slightly pinched

00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:38.430
along the
perpendicular direction

00:17:38.430 --> 00:17:41.600
due to gravitational
contraction.

00:17:41.600 --> 00:17:42.970
This is observed, actually.

00:17:42.970 --> 00:17:48.510
So here's an observation with
the SMA telescope in Hawaii,

00:17:48.510 --> 00:17:52.410
looking at field lines
in a star forming object.

00:17:52.410 --> 00:17:55.040
And you can also,
even just by eye,

00:17:55.040 --> 00:17:59.080
see this pinching effect of
the field line, perpendicular

00:17:59.080 --> 00:18:00.870
to the collapse.

00:18:00.870 --> 00:18:03.790
This is called a so-called
hourglass morphology,

00:18:03.790 --> 00:18:06.130
or an hourglass shape
in the magnetic field.

00:18:06.130 --> 00:18:09.430
And this indicates that the
magnetic field is strong.

00:18:09.430 --> 00:18:11.830
OK, what does strong mean?

00:18:11.830 --> 00:18:15.550
Well, your fridge
magnet has a strength

00:18:15.550 --> 00:18:18.650
of roughly 50 gauss or so.

00:18:18.650 --> 00:18:22.580
These fields are at the
microgauss scale, so 10

00:18:22.580 --> 00:18:24.340
to the minus sixth.

00:18:24.340 --> 00:18:27.160
And that's a pretty
big difference,

00:18:27.160 --> 00:18:30.280
but for a molecular cloud,
this is actually very strong.

00:18:30.280 --> 00:18:34.090
So in this case, we might expect
that the magnetic forces are

00:18:34.090 --> 00:18:36.780
very strong, stronger than
things like turbulence

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:39.080
or maybe even the
gravity itself.

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:41.430
So things look very ordered.

00:18:41.430 --> 00:18:44.270
However, in other
observations-- so this

00:18:44.270 --> 00:18:46.800
is observations of
dust polarization

00:18:46.800 --> 00:18:50.330
from the Planck satellite,
so similar to what

00:18:50.330 --> 00:18:51.160
Cora was showing.

00:18:51.160 --> 00:18:54.400
But instead, we're actually
now interested in what's

00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:56.970
happening in the galaxy.

00:18:56.970 --> 00:18:59.540
In this case, the fields
look very random, right.

00:18:59.540 --> 00:19:02.090
So you can see the field lines
here looking very chaotic.

00:19:02.090 --> 00:19:04.790
And this might be a situation
where things like turbulence,

00:19:04.790 --> 00:19:07.920
which wants to
randomize the field,

00:19:07.920 --> 00:19:11.540
is stronger than
the magnetic forces.

00:19:11.540 --> 00:19:14.880
So how can we further study the
effects of the magnetic field

00:19:14.880 --> 00:19:15.720
in star formations?

00:19:15.720 --> 00:19:17.790
It's very complicated,
we need to go back

00:19:17.790 --> 00:19:19.650
to our numerical simulations.

00:19:19.650 --> 00:19:22.080
And so I'm going to show you
some very, very recent state

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:25.120
of the art numerical
simulations that we've recently

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:28.700
performed in order to study the
effect of the magnetic field

00:19:28.700 --> 00:19:32.120
in a collapsing
stellar environment.

00:19:32.120 --> 00:19:36.010
And we can do this sort
of in this typical way

00:19:36.010 --> 00:19:38.630
where we observe some sort
of real world phenomenon.

00:19:38.630 --> 00:19:43.000
So as an example, I've shown
you this instability that

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.090
can actually form
in clouds, it's

00:19:45.090 --> 00:19:47.160
called the Kelvin-Hulmholtz
Instability, where

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:49.280
you have two shearing flows.

00:19:49.280 --> 00:19:51.250
You say, I want to
try to simulate this.

00:19:51.250 --> 00:19:54.910
I want to include fluid dynamics
equations, mass conservation,

00:19:54.910 --> 00:19:57.830
momentum conservation,
energy conservation,

00:19:57.830 --> 00:20:02.490
and I want to try to simulate
this on a parallel computing

00:20:02.490 --> 00:20:03.060
resource.

00:20:03.060 --> 00:20:06.080
We have a very nice one here
at Harvard called Odyssey.

00:20:06.080 --> 00:20:09.320
And then ultimately-- I'll
restart that movie for you.

00:20:09.320 --> 00:20:14.630
We use a particular numerical
simulation, so in this case

00:20:14.630 --> 00:20:17.290
we've used the AREPO code,
which is a code where

00:20:17.290 --> 00:20:19.510
the grid points
in the simulation

00:20:19.510 --> 00:20:22.209
actually move with the fluid
and change with the fluid.

00:20:22.209 --> 00:20:24.000
So they're not static,
and you can actually

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:27.300
model very precisely
instabilities, turbulence,

00:20:27.300 --> 00:20:29.460
et cetera.

00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:31.400
So this is the code we used.

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:35.630
This code is unique, in
that we are able then to,

00:20:35.630 --> 00:20:39.210
following the fluid flow
as it evolves with gravity,

00:20:39.210 --> 00:20:41.960
we are able to follow it
down over many, many orders

00:20:41.960 --> 00:20:43.480
of magnitude and scale.

00:20:43.480 --> 00:20:47.800
So going from 16 light years
down to 100 astronomical units.

00:20:47.800 --> 00:20:52.100
An astronomical unit is about
93 million miles, the distance

00:20:52.100 --> 00:20:53.540
of the sun and the Earth.

00:20:53.540 --> 00:20:55.740
So this is a huge
range of scales.

00:20:55.740 --> 00:20:58.960
We're also able to go over
a huge range of densities,

00:20:58.960 --> 00:21:01.030
many orders of magnitude
of density going

00:21:01.030 --> 00:21:05.120
from the diffuse cloud scales,
down to the very dense cores,

00:21:05.120 --> 00:21:06.610
where the stars are forming.

00:21:06.610 --> 00:21:09.550
And the original
thing we've done here

00:21:09.550 --> 00:21:12.530
and additional to that, is we
have four of the simulations.

00:21:12.530 --> 00:21:15.210
These simulations are very
computationally expensive.

00:21:15.210 --> 00:21:18.380
Four different simulations, each
with a different magnetic field

00:21:18.380 --> 00:21:19.900
strength, so we
can really study,

00:21:19.900 --> 00:21:23.560
in depth, the interaction
of the magnetic field

00:21:23.560 --> 00:21:25.590
and the collapse of the cloud.

00:21:25.590 --> 00:21:27.535
So I'm going to show
you these simulations.

00:21:27.535 --> 00:21:29.160
I'm going to show
you all four of them,

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:31.790
and just keep your eye
on the top of the screen.

00:21:31.790 --> 00:21:35.640
This is the magnetic field
strength in microgauss.

00:21:35.640 --> 00:21:37.220
Here's the first simulation.

00:21:37.220 --> 00:21:40.250
And I'm going to show you all
four in a very similar way.

00:21:40.250 --> 00:21:42.870
Just to give you some
idea of the scale here,

00:21:42.870 --> 00:21:46.060
so this is about 15,
16 light years across.

00:21:46.060 --> 00:21:48.110
This is the cloud
scale, you can see

00:21:48.110 --> 00:21:51.180
by eye the density structure
is very fractal, very

00:21:51.180 --> 00:21:52.640
turbulent looking.

00:21:52.640 --> 00:21:55.900
And this panel here,
this inset here,

00:21:55.900 --> 00:22:00.590
is one pixel, zoomed in one
pixel from this image here.

00:22:00.590 --> 00:22:03.450
So we're talking about
huge ranges of scales.

00:22:03.450 --> 00:22:07.270
And you can already see that
there's a filamentary structure

00:22:07.270 --> 00:22:09.650
here, and then this panel
here is even further

00:22:09.650 --> 00:22:13.520
zoomed in, a region where
a star would be forming.

00:22:13.520 --> 00:22:15.580
Now what does the
magnetic field look like?

00:22:15.580 --> 00:22:18.910
This case has a very
weak magnetic field.

00:22:18.910 --> 00:22:23.070
And if I over plot the
orientation of the field lines,

00:22:23.070 --> 00:22:24.750
it looks pretty random.

00:22:24.750 --> 00:22:29.380
So the field is somewhat
ordered on the largest scales,

00:22:29.380 --> 00:22:31.380
but as you go to the
smaller and smaller scales,

00:22:31.380 --> 00:22:32.570
it's pretty random.

00:22:32.570 --> 00:22:35.160
It's changing its orientation
at every sort of step

00:22:35.160 --> 00:22:36.580
that we go down.

00:22:36.580 --> 00:22:38.570
We expect that
because in this case,

00:22:38.570 --> 00:22:40.370
we have a very weak field.

00:22:40.370 --> 00:22:42.930
Now if we increase the
field strength-- so again,

00:22:42.930 --> 00:22:45.620
here's the density structure
that you're seeing,

00:22:45.620 --> 00:22:47.380
and here's the magnetic field.

00:22:47.380 --> 00:22:51.120
It's already slightly a little
bit more ordered at each scale,

00:22:51.120 --> 00:22:53.610
because we've increased
the field strength.

00:22:53.610 --> 00:22:56.240
And we can continue to
increase the field strength,

00:22:56.240 --> 00:22:59.245
so this is our second
most strong field case.

00:22:59.245 --> 00:23:00.620
You can see now
the large scales,

00:23:00.620 --> 00:23:03.550
you have a very
uniform, ordered field,

00:23:03.550 --> 00:23:07.230
and this somewhat persists
down to the smaller fields.

00:23:07.230 --> 00:23:10.360
However, in this case it
still looks fairly random.

00:23:10.360 --> 00:23:12.984
Finally, this is the
highest field strength.

00:23:12.984 --> 00:23:15.400
Things look actually quite
different from the other cases.

00:23:15.400 --> 00:23:17.890
So if you compare the
density fields, for example,

00:23:17.890 --> 00:23:21.110
especially at the smaller scales
where stars are able to form,

00:23:21.110 --> 00:23:23.540
now there's this very
nice filamentary structure

00:23:23.540 --> 00:23:24.300
that's formed.

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:26.990
In the case where
the magnetic field

00:23:26.990 --> 00:23:30.400
is higher in terms of its
energy and then the turbulence

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:31.870
and the gravity.

00:23:31.870 --> 00:23:34.760
And if we look at the
corresponding field structure,

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:39.142
we said it's extremely ordered,
all the way down through all

00:23:39.142 --> 00:23:40.850
these different scales
of star formation.

00:23:40.850 --> 00:23:43.050
So once you get to
this very smallest

00:23:43.050 --> 00:23:45.100
scales of star
formation, you actually

00:23:45.100 --> 00:23:48.610
start to also see this very
nice hourglass morphology

00:23:48.610 --> 00:23:53.360
that we predicted when gravity
was very strong, interacting

00:23:53.360 --> 00:23:55.344
with a magnetic field.

00:23:55.344 --> 00:23:57.010
So this is what the
simulations tell us.

00:23:57.010 --> 00:23:59.760
They tell us that there are sort
of two modes of star formation.

00:23:59.760 --> 00:24:04.160
One where there's random,
turbulent energy that's

00:24:04.160 --> 00:24:06.610
dominant over magnetic
energy, and another

00:24:06.610 --> 00:24:10.150
where the magnetic field sort
of dominates the collapse.

00:24:10.150 --> 00:24:13.650
This is from simulations,
what can observations tell us?

00:24:13.650 --> 00:24:16.980
How can we better compare
these two observations

00:24:16.980 --> 00:24:18.480
and simulations?

00:24:18.480 --> 00:24:21.424
Well, I've been harping on
the advance of the simulations

00:24:21.424 --> 00:24:23.090
that we can go through
all these scales,

00:24:23.090 --> 00:24:24.714
include all these
physics, but actually

00:24:24.714 --> 00:24:26.520
the observations have
also been advancing.

00:24:26.520 --> 00:24:28.730
So meanwhile, we've
been able to go

00:24:28.730 --> 00:24:31.690
from larger and larger
scales with the observations

00:24:31.690 --> 00:24:32.550
to smaller scales.

00:24:32.550 --> 00:24:35.010
And so ALMA, the
ALMA telescope, which

00:24:35.010 --> 00:24:37.090
is a millimeter wave
telescope in Chile

00:24:37.090 --> 00:24:40.450
has really opened up a
very high sensitivity,

00:24:40.450 --> 00:24:44.180
high resolution observations
for star forming regions.

00:24:44.180 --> 00:24:47.840
And so we can combine previous
generation instruments

00:24:47.840 --> 00:24:51.500
like the CARMA telescope
and the JCMT telescope

00:24:51.500 --> 00:24:55.760
to get different scales of the
star formation process as well.

00:24:55.760 --> 00:24:58.630
So the JCMT data is
giving large scales, so

00:24:58.630 --> 00:25:01.760
sort of a tenth of a
parsec type scales.

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:03.890
CARMA's scales and
ALMA's scales are giving

00:25:03.890 --> 00:25:05.760
this medium and smaller scales.

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:08.470
And so I'll show you
one particular object

00:25:08.470 --> 00:25:12.440
from a recent study that
my collaborators at Harvard

00:25:12.440 --> 00:25:16.380
and myself have performed
using these different data

00:25:16.380 --> 00:25:20.040
sets of a particular
object called Serpens-8.

00:25:20.040 --> 00:25:22.920
Here's the JCMT data,
so this is something

00:25:22.920 --> 00:25:26.100
like a tenth of a parsec,
down to the CARMA data,

00:25:26.100 --> 00:25:30.800
down to this finest resolution,
which ALMA has just now opened

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:31.810
up for us.

00:25:31.810 --> 00:25:35.120
And all of these data
also have polarization,

00:25:35.120 --> 00:25:38.270
so they all have magnetic field
orientation measurements, which

00:25:38.270 --> 00:25:39.780
I'm showing you down here.

00:25:39.780 --> 00:25:42.910
And you can see that the
field looks very random.

00:25:42.910 --> 00:25:46.500
And it looks very random all
the way down towards the scales

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:48.490
of the ALMA data.

00:25:48.490 --> 00:25:51.630
So this is actually
very similar to what

00:25:51.630 --> 00:25:55.470
we found in the simulations
where the field is very weak.

00:25:55.470 --> 00:26:00.760
And so it seems that this ALMA
scale magnetic field is not

00:26:00.760 --> 00:26:04.260
following the field from
the very largest scales.

00:26:04.260 --> 00:26:07.530
That's in contrast to this
nice hourglass picture.

00:26:07.530 --> 00:26:10.160
So in some cases we
see an hourglass type

00:26:10.160 --> 00:26:13.470
of morphology, that indicates
the field is very strong.

00:26:13.470 --> 00:26:15.410
In other cases,
like in Serpens-8,

00:26:15.410 --> 00:26:17.440
we found that
turbulence is perhaps

00:26:17.440 --> 00:26:20.360
more important in shaping
the field morphology.

00:26:20.360 --> 00:26:24.000
And this is in
contrast to decades

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:26.950
of theoretical and
observational works, which

00:26:26.950 --> 00:26:29.480
say that you should always
form this hourglass.

00:26:29.480 --> 00:26:32.870
So in this case we
did not see that.

00:26:32.870 --> 00:26:36.580
So I would like to conclude,
going back to our quote

00:26:36.580 --> 00:26:39.630
from Carl, "We are all
made of starstuff."

00:26:39.630 --> 00:26:43.490
If we really want to
understand how we got here,

00:26:43.490 --> 00:26:45.660
how our star was
formed, we really

00:26:45.660 --> 00:26:47.880
have to take into all
the complicated galaxy

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:51.780
physics, including turbulence,
including magnetic fields.

00:26:51.780 --> 00:26:54.080
And so it's complicated.

00:26:54.080 --> 00:26:56.760
Simulations are
really going to be

00:26:56.760 --> 00:27:00.590
key to answering a lot of
galaxy physics questions, star

00:27:00.590 --> 00:27:02.460
formation just
being one of them.

00:27:02.460 --> 00:27:06.710
And I think really, in terms
of the star formation paradigm,

00:27:06.710 --> 00:27:09.440
we're going to be able to move
towards a predictive theory

00:27:09.440 --> 00:27:11.660
of star formation,
because we understand

00:27:11.660 --> 00:27:13.020
the fluid dynamics better.

00:27:13.020 --> 00:27:17.160
Because we understand turbulence
and magnetic fields in a better

00:27:17.160 --> 00:27:17.800
way.

