00:29:51.440 --> 00:29:54.200
I'm not talking about aliens.

00:29:54.200 --> 00:29:56.620
I'm not going to be talking
about intelligent life today.

00:29:56.620 --> 00:29:58.990
I'm really only
talking about microbes,

00:29:58.990 --> 00:30:01.370
like these single
celled organisms

00:30:01.370 --> 00:30:04.120
that we might be able to
detect the signs of their life

00:30:04.120 --> 00:30:06.040
in the atmosphere
of another planet.

00:30:06.040 --> 00:30:08.070
And so how could we do this?

00:30:08.070 --> 00:30:11.950
Well, one of the thing to do is
by looking for biosignatures.

00:30:11.950 --> 00:30:14.810
And I would argue that
the strongest biosignature

00:30:14.810 --> 00:30:17.400
is something like an
oxidizing and reducing gas

00:30:17.400 --> 00:30:19.370
in combination.

00:30:19.370 --> 00:30:21.820
On Earth, that's something
like oxygen and ozone,

00:30:21.820 --> 00:30:24.700
or ozone in combination
with methane.

00:30:24.700 --> 00:30:27.820
But individually, you can get
either of these abiotically.

00:30:27.820 --> 00:30:32.260
For example, UV light can
split water and carbon dioxide,

00:30:32.260 --> 00:30:35.550
and you can be left behind
with oxygen or ozone,

00:30:35.550 --> 00:30:38.010
and you get methane
from vulcanism

00:30:38.010 --> 00:30:40.310
or from hydrothermal vents.

00:30:40.310 --> 00:30:44.850
And so these by themselves
are not good biosignatures.

00:30:44.850 --> 00:30:47.000
On Earth, though,
you have biology

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:50.660
giving large fluxes of both
gases, of oxygen the methane.

00:30:50.660 --> 00:30:54.630
But without biology,
these gases would

00:30:54.630 --> 00:30:57.470
destruct in the atmosphere,
and you wouldn't necessarily

00:30:57.470 --> 00:31:00.180
see them together in the
atmosphere of an exoplanet.

00:31:00.180 --> 00:31:03.460
So this is why we go
back to that definition.

00:31:03.460 --> 00:31:07.220
Also, biosignatures
require context.

00:31:07.220 --> 00:31:09.230
Things like, can
we get constraints

00:31:09.230 --> 00:31:11.290
on the surface temperature?

00:31:11.290 --> 00:31:13.430
Is it a rocky planet?

00:31:13.430 --> 00:31:17.080
Does it have bio vital
indicators like CO2 and water?

00:31:17.080 --> 00:31:20.670
Now CO2 and water by themselves
are not biosignatures,

00:31:20.670 --> 00:31:24.860
because they can be around
in the whole universe

00:31:24.860 --> 00:31:27.040
just abiotically, but
they are useful for us

00:31:27.040 --> 00:31:28.980
to detect because
they indicate food

00:31:28.980 --> 00:31:33.500
and habitability and
greenhouse gas on the planet.

00:31:33.500 --> 00:31:36.520
Other biosignatures that you
might have heard talked about

00:31:36.520 --> 00:31:39.230
are things like N2O,
methylchloride, or dimethyl

00:31:39.230 --> 00:31:43.350
sulfide, and maybe ammonia in a
hydrogen dominated atmosphere.

00:31:43.350 --> 00:31:44.960
And these, though
they're produced

00:31:44.960 --> 00:31:47.970
in much smaller abundances,
are useful to think about

00:31:47.970 --> 00:31:53.140
because they don't have
any abiotic known source.

00:31:53.140 --> 00:31:55.800
So my research,
though, is how could we

00:31:55.800 --> 00:31:59.230
detect these biosignatures
around other stars?

00:31:59.230 --> 00:32:00.830
And I love this
pale blue dot image,

00:32:00.830 --> 00:32:04.000
which I'm sure many of you are
familiar with, when Voyager

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:07.050
went out past the orbit of Pluto
and turned around, and took

00:32:07.050 --> 00:32:09.160
this snapshot of our planet.

00:32:09.160 --> 00:32:10.920
And here it is.

00:32:10.920 --> 00:32:16.370
And in that image, you can take
a spectra the light from that

00:32:16.370 --> 00:32:20.324
and see various signs
of life on our planet.

00:32:20.324 --> 00:32:21.740
In particular, you
would be seeing

00:32:21.740 --> 00:32:26.390
that combination of methane
and oxygen and ozone.

00:32:26.390 --> 00:32:32.720
And also we have surface
vegetation signal as well.

00:32:32.720 --> 00:32:34.060
Right now, we're not there.

00:32:34.060 --> 00:32:35.601
I just want to be
clear we're talking

00:32:35.601 --> 00:32:37.120
about future observations.

00:32:37.120 --> 00:32:40.490
So we're in indirect
detection, not transmission,

00:32:40.490 --> 00:32:42.040
but in direct
detection we're now

00:32:42.040 --> 00:32:44.130
detecting hot, giant planets.

00:32:44.130 --> 00:32:48.340
And for transmission we're able
to do superearths, warm, really

00:32:48.340 --> 00:32:50.310
warm or hot superearths.

00:32:50.310 --> 00:32:53.800
So really, these sorts of
observations are future.

00:32:53.800 --> 00:32:56.870
And this just shows
you the spectra

00:32:56.870 --> 00:32:59.690
of three terrestial planets
that we all know and love,

00:32:59.690 --> 00:33:01.460
the Earth, Venus, and Mars.

00:33:01.460 --> 00:33:05.710
And you can see that those
spectra are very different.

00:33:05.710 --> 00:33:08.400
And we expect the
universe to provide us

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:12.290
with an abundance of
different types of planets,

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:13.910
and we are hoping
that we're going

00:33:13.910 --> 00:33:16.310
to be able to distinguish the
different types of planets

00:33:16.310 --> 00:33:18.180
by looking at
something like this,

00:33:18.180 --> 00:33:20.210
and getting spectra
from the planets,

00:33:20.210 --> 00:33:24.400
and being able to tease out how
does one planet look different

00:33:24.400 --> 00:33:26.810
from another.

00:33:26.810 --> 00:33:29.230
Our first opportunity
to be able to do this

00:33:29.230 --> 00:33:31.450
is going to be with the
James Webb Space Telescope,

00:33:31.450 --> 00:33:34.950
launching in 2018, as well
as with some of these large,

00:33:34.950 --> 00:33:36.960
ground based observatories
like the GMT,

00:33:36.960 --> 00:33:41.780
the E-ELT, and the TMT that
are being built in the 2020s.

00:33:41.780 --> 00:33:46.550
And even more so that
the next generation

00:33:46.550 --> 00:33:49.480
of missions, something that
in the astronomy community we

00:33:49.480 --> 00:33:53.320
term LUVOIR or HDST is
this future mission.

00:33:53.320 --> 00:33:56.540
Something that's more like a
12 meter space based telescope.

00:33:56.540 --> 00:33:59.320
This would be able to
get the direct light

00:33:59.320 --> 00:34:02.770
from these planets, of
habitable, Earthlike planets

00:34:02.770 --> 00:34:04.490
much more easily.

00:34:04.490 --> 00:34:06.790
And so that's kind
of the trajectory

00:34:06.790 --> 00:34:08.570
of where our technology
is going and where

00:34:08.570 --> 00:34:13.780
we're hoping to aim our
future research efforts.

00:34:13.780 --> 00:34:17.040
So my work, though, is
interested in how does the star

00:34:17.040 --> 00:34:20.590
impact the atmosphere,
the spectral features,

00:34:20.590 --> 00:34:23.210
and the biosignatures
around these planets.

00:34:23.210 --> 00:34:27.590
And so I'm going to talk a
lot about FGKM stars today,

00:34:27.590 --> 00:34:30.002
particularly the M stars.

00:34:30.002 --> 00:34:32.210
By and large, you're going
from a high UV environment

00:34:32.210 --> 00:34:35.550
for F stars, down to low
UV, though then M stars also

00:34:35.550 --> 00:34:39.760
have a spike in UV environment.

00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:44.800
And these-- FGKM is,
again, just bigger, hotter

00:34:44.800 --> 00:34:46.989
down to the cooler
ones for those of you

00:34:46.989 --> 00:34:49.900
who are not familiar
with that terminology.

00:34:49.900 --> 00:34:53.530
And UV destroys
some biosignatures.

00:34:53.530 --> 00:34:55.179
So it could destroy,
say, methane

00:34:55.179 --> 00:34:57.262
for example in the atmosphere,
and that might make

00:34:57.262 --> 00:34:58.800
it harder to detect for us.

00:34:58.800 --> 00:35:02.250
But on the other hand, UV
produces other biosignatures

00:35:02.250 --> 00:35:05.810
like ozone, making that
one then easier to detect.

00:35:05.810 --> 00:35:08.900
So UV is kind of a
mixed bag in our ability

00:35:08.900 --> 00:35:11.970
to detect the biosignatures
around these future planets

00:35:11.970 --> 00:35:13.670
that we're going to observe.

00:35:13.670 --> 00:35:17.040
In addition to
that, it's the ratio

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:20.950
of the far UV, so the shorter
wavelength, higher energy UV,

00:35:20.950 --> 00:35:25.830
to be near UV, or
the lower energy UV.

00:35:25.830 --> 00:35:26.880
That matters.

00:35:26.880 --> 00:35:29.740
And you can see this
in the reaction rates

00:35:29.740 --> 00:35:33.190
for the production and
destruction of ozone.

00:35:33.190 --> 00:35:37.060
So here, you can see that
the production of ozone

00:35:37.060 --> 00:35:42.630
is dependent on this
far UV energy photons.

00:35:42.630 --> 00:35:47.415
But the destruction depends
more on the near UV light,

00:35:47.415 --> 00:35:49.250
and can be produced that way.

00:35:49.250 --> 00:35:52.000
So it's not just how much
UV you have in general,

00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:54.570
it's where in the UV
spectrum you have.

00:35:54.570 --> 00:35:57.720
We want to have accurate
observations of the star UV

00:35:57.720 --> 00:36:01.770
in order to understand
our future observations.

00:36:01.770 --> 00:36:03.490
So I do modeling.

00:36:03.490 --> 00:36:07.400
This is me, before
I dyed my hair red.

00:36:07.400 --> 00:36:11.930
And as Blakesley said,
we can learn a lot

00:36:11.930 --> 00:36:14.390
from computer modeling.

00:36:14.390 --> 00:36:16.710
This is the only time
