00:36:19.230 --> 00:36:24.490
And so we do this to model
these atmospheres of exoplanets,

00:36:24.490 --> 00:36:26.690
and were interested in
particular questions

00:36:26.690 --> 00:36:30.160
like what wavelengths
should we be looking at?

00:36:30.160 --> 00:36:33.010
What resolution
should we be looking

00:36:33.010 --> 00:36:36.520
to build our spectrometers
for to detect these features?

00:36:36.520 --> 00:36:38.420
And how big of a
telescope do we need?

00:36:38.420 --> 00:36:40.820
Do we need that LUVOIR
sized telescope?

00:36:40.820 --> 00:36:43.040
Can we go, you know,
instead of 12 meters could

00:36:43.040 --> 00:36:43.920
we do 10 meters?

00:36:43.920 --> 00:36:46.190
You know, and these
sorts of questions

00:36:46.190 --> 00:36:48.070
are the type of
questions that I hope

00:36:48.070 --> 00:36:51.280
that my work will help answer.

00:36:51.280 --> 00:36:56.150
So I mentioned the FGKM stars,
and today just due to interest

00:36:56.150 --> 00:36:58.720
of time, I'm going to really
focus on these M stars,

00:36:58.720 --> 00:37:01.080
because these are very
interesting stars.

00:37:01.080 --> 00:37:04.710
So the M stars are the
coolest stellar type,

00:37:04.710 --> 00:37:06.830
and they're much
smaller than our sun.

00:37:09.570 --> 00:37:12.490
But they make up
75% of the stars

00:37:12.490 --> 00:37:15.150
in our universe and
solar neighborhood.

00:37:15.150 --> 00:37:20.080
So in the about the 300
or so closest stars to us,

00:37:20.080 --> 00:37:23.830
246 of them are M stars.

00:37:23.830 --> 00:37:26.080
And so these are going
to be our nearest targets

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:30.770
and are just very common places
that we would expect to look.

00:37:30.770 --> 00:37:32.950
I love animation
by Elizabeth here,

00:37:32.950 --> 00:37:36.190
where this is the night
sky as you normally see it.

00:37:36.190 --> 00:37:39.170
And then now, if you
turn on what it would

00:37:39.170 --> 00:37:40.480
look like with the M stars.

00:37:40.480 --> 00:37:42.188
I don't know if you
can see the contrast.

00:37:42.188 --> 00:37:44.400
Now they're starting to
