So you can see here is say an
Earth sized planet crossing

00:38:10.100 --> 00:38:11.600
in front of an an
M star, it's going

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:15.340
to create much bigger depth than
an Earth like planet crossing

00:38:15.340 --> 00:38:18.900
it in front of a star that
something similar to the sun.

00:38:18.900 --> 00:38:22.620
And so, this is
one reason why we

00:38:22.620 --> 00:38:24.960
want to also look at M stars.

00:38:24.960 --> 00:38:28.686
In addition these
planets around M stars,

00:38:28.686 --> 00:38:30.060
because they're
cooler, are going

00:38:30.060 --> 00:38:32.460
to be orbiting at
much closer distances.

00:38:32.460 --> 00:38:35.810
So that means their habitable
zones are closer, in right.

00:38:35.810 --> 00:38:37.960
And so this is a
diagram of stellar type

00:38:37.960 --> 00:38:40.020
here, and the habitable zone.

00:38:40.020 --> 00:38:42.272
So here's say, our sun,
and here's the Earth,

00:38:42.272 --> 00:38:43.480
that's in the habitable zone.

00:38:43.480 --> 00:38:46.210
But for an M star,
the habitable zone

00:38:46.210 --> 00:38:48.210
is much closer to that star.

00:38:48.210 --> 00:38:52.380
So it's orbiting maybe every
20 days instead of once a year.

00:38:52.380 --> 00:38:54.810
And if we're trying to add
up especially transits,

00:38:54.810 --> 00:38:56.290
that's much more
convenient for us,

00:38:56.290 --> 00:38:59.200
because we don't have to wait
for observations once a year.

00:38:59.200 --> 00:39:02.280
We can get them every
10, 20, 30 days,

00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:05.520
depending on the star type.

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:07.650
And the most exciting
thing, I think,

00:39:07.650 --> 00:39:09.860
in one of the
discoveries recently

00:39:09.860 --> 00:39:13.350
is that one in four M dwarfs
have a habitable planet.

00:39:13.350 --> 00:39:15.310
That's amazing,
because M stars are

00:39:15.310 --> 00:39:17.950
the most abundant
stars in our universe

00:39:17.950 --> 00:39:19.460
and in our solar neighborhood.

00:39:19.460 --> 00:39:23.700
And it appears that terrestrial,
earth like planets form

00:39:23.700 --> 00:39:25.650
quite frequently around them.

00:39:25.650 --> 00:39:29.400
So they're good places
for us to follow up.

00:39:29.400 --> 00:39:31.080
They have some problems.

00:39:31.080 --> 00:39:33.510
One is they have
a lot of flares,

00:39:33.510 --> 00:39:36.700
and they might be
pretty difficult places

00:39:36.700 --> 00:39:38.400
to live around.

00:39:38.400 --> 00:39:43.200
In particular, early
M stars remain active,

00:39:43.200 --> 00:39:46.250
even early M stars, which
are the hotter M stars here,

00:39:46.250 --> 00:39:50.260
remain active for one
to two billion years.

00:39:50.260 --> 00:39:52.040
For comparison, our
sun remained active

00:39:52.040 --> 00:39:53.980
for, say, half a billion years.

00:39:53.980 --> 00:39:59.100
And later M stars,
past M4 or so in type,

00:39:59.100 --> 00:40:01.722
those later M stars
remain active for six

00:40:01.722 --> 00:40:02.680
to eight billion years.

00:40:02.680 --> 00:40:06.240
So this is the amount of
time that they remain active

00:40:06.240 --> 00:40:07.910
with spectral type.

00:40:07.910 --> 00:40:11.780
And so that makes our follow
up and understanding what's

00:40:11.780 --> 00:40:13.770
going on is going to
be more difficult.

00:40:13.770 --> 00:40:16.270
Also, M stars are just very
hard to characterize in general,

00:40:16.270 --> 00:40:18.950
and there's a lot of
work being done on that.

00:40:18.950 --> 00:40:22.630
So I'm going to go through
kind of a little cartoon

00:40:22.630 --> 00:40:25.530
drawing of the
differences between what

00:40:25.530 --> 00:40:29.110
I'm going to call an active M
star and an inactive M star,

00:40:29.110 --> 00:40:31.460
and then some of the
observations that we have,

00:40:31.460 --> 00:40:33.370
and talk about how
that influences

00:40:33.370 --> 00:40:35.760
our modeling of these planets.

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:39.530
So this would be something like
an active M star spectrrum.

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:44.230
And this is the theoretical
minimum limit of activity.

00:40:44.230 --> 00:40:48.280
So that's just assuming--
going back to Blakesley's point

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:52.710
that magnetic fields are really
hard-- the UV in a lot of stars

00:40:52.710 --> 00:40:55.800
is driven by magnetic field
activity in the chromosphere.

00:40:55.800 --> 00:40:58.340
And say you didn't have
that around an M star,

00:40:58.340 --> 00:40:59.790
you only had just
the temperature

00:40:59.790 --> 00:41:01.880
in the photosphere
radiating, then

00:41:01.880 --> 00:41:05.630
this would be the minimum
amount of UV that you would get.

00:41:05.630 --> 00:41:08.720
But in general, when we
measure these older M stars,

00:41:08.720 --> 00:41:11.770
we get something more like this.

00:41:11.770 --> 00:41:13.320
Something in the middle.

00:41:13.320 --> 00:41:17.980
And we actually don't yet know
what the floor of the UV is.

00:41:17.980 --> 00:41:19.470
How low can we go.

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:21.470
Because for some of
these stars, we only

00:41:21.470 --> 00:41:23.190
have the emission
peaks observed.

00:41:23.190 --> 00:41:27.730
We actually don't know where
the floor of the continuum is.

00:41:27.730 --> 00:41:30.382
So for example, could it
be down here, or maybe

00:41:30.382 --> 00:41:32.090
it's all the way down
to the photosphere.

00:41:32.090 --> 00:41:34.190
We don't yet have
that, answer and we're

00:41:34.190 --> 00:41:38.170
trying to-- we need more
observations of these stars

00:41:38.170 --> 00:41:41.390
to probe the range
of expected UVs,

00:41:41.390 --> 00:41:43.480
and particularly the
lower range of UVs

00:41:43.480 --> 00:41:45.790
that we might expect to get.

00:41:45.790 --> 00:41:47.290
Also, I'm going to
talk a little bit

00:41:47.290 --> 00:41:50.920
about the known false
positives for oxygen and ozone.

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:55.190
So oxygen on Earth, all
21%, is produced by life,

00:41:55.190 --> 00:41:57.190
but we have thought
about some ways

00:41:57.190 --> 00:41:59.160
that you could create
it without life.

00:41:59.160 --> 00:42:03.610
And so these are just a handful
of the six or so commonly

00:42:03.610 --> 00:42:06.420
talked about false
positive mechanisms,

00:42:06.420 --> 00:42:08.300
and what's really
interesting about this

00:42:08.300 --> 00:42:13.220
is about a majority of them
really are most common,

00:42:13.220 --> 00:42:16.160
or we expect to be most
common, are only around planets

00:42:16.160 --> 00:42:17.330
orbiting M dwarfs.

00:42:17.330 --> 00:42:20.640
So again, understanding
M dwarfs and their UV

00:42:20.640 --> 00:42:21.700
is really important.

00:42:21.700 --> 00:42:26.420
And all of these mechanisms
revolve around the UV

00:42:26.420 --> 00:42:29.080
environment of these stars.

00:42:29.080 --> 00:42:33.336
So I'm going to go
through one example

00:42:33.336 --> 00:42:36.510
of a false positive
generations of an M star.

00:42:36.510 --> 00:42:40.560
So M stars can be
really-- before they

00:42:40.560 --> 00:42:42.902
join the main sequence,
they're really luminous.

00:42:42.902 --> 00:42:44.360
They have this
super luminous phase

00:42:44.360 --> 00:42:45.920
that lasts quite a long time.

00:42:45.920 --> 00:42:47.060
They're very active.

00:42:47.060 --> 00:42:49.520
And during that phase, if
the planet that's orbiting it

00:42:49.520 --> 00:42:55.780
has water, that water is going
to be photolyzed from UV light

00:42:55.780 --> 00:42:56.500
reaching it.

00:42:56.500 --> 00:42:58.990
And it's going to
break apart the water,

00:42:58.990 --> 00:43:02.827
and the hydrogen is
going to escape to space,

00:43:02.827 --> 00:43:03.910
and it's going to be done.

00:43:03.910 --> 00:43:06.410
And you're going to permanently
maybe desiccate that planet.

00:43:06.410 --> 00:43:09.440
It's going to turn
into like a Dune world.

00:43:09.440 --> 00:43:12.720
And unless you have later
water delivery, of course,

00:43:12.720 --> 00:43:14.060
but this is a concern.

00:43:14.060 --> 00:43:16.050
And if you were to
observe such a planet,

00:43:16.050 --> 00:43:20.130
you might see a buildup of
oxygen in that atmosphere,

00:43:20.130 --> 00:43:22.070
depending on how
much of that oxygen

00:43:22.070 --> 00:43:26.630
is going to then later
react with the surface.

00:43:26.630 --> 00:43:28.950
Which is something
that a lot of research

00:43:28.950 --> 00:43:32.530
has been going on into
that problem as well.

00:43:32.530 --> 00:43:33.960
Another example
of that, was this

00:43:33.960 --> 00:43:35.459
was the first
example, I think, that

00:43:35.459 --> 00:43:38.640
proposed of abiotic
oxygen, was for planets

00:43:38.640 --> 00:43:40.400
that are on just
on the inner edge--

00:43:40.400 --> 00:43:42.560
before the inner edge
of the habitable zone,

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:45.990
so they're all a little
too hot, shall we say.

00:43:45.990 --> 00:43:48.520
And they go through a
runaway greenhouse effect.

00:43:48.520 --> 00:43:49.900
So you can imagine
this scenario,

00:43:49.900 --> 00:43:51.410
it's basically the same thing.

00:43:51.410 --> 00:43:55.490
You have the UV light from the
star breaking apart the water,

00:43:55.490 --> 00:43:59.170
and you get the hydrogen
escaping to space,

00:43:59.170 --> 00:44:01.490
and your oxygen's left behind.

00:44:01.490 --> 00:44:04.700
So again, this goes
back to the point

00:44:04.700 --> 00:44:07.185
that I made at the beginning,
is that to detect life

00:44:07.185 --> 00:44:08.560
on another planet,
is we're going

00:44:08.560 --> 00:44:10.600
to need a combination of gases.

00:44:10.600 --> 00:44:12.750
One gas is probably
not going to be enough.

00:44:12.750 --> 00:44:16.750
We're going to need context
and multiple gases in order

00:44:16.750 --> 00:44:19.160
to understand what we're seeing.

00:44:19.160 --> 00:44:22.010
And so this goes back to
the idea that was first

00:44:22.010 --> 00:44:25.110
proposed a long time ago
with Lovelock and Carl Sagan,

00:44:25.110 --> 00:44:27.080
and a lot of people
have talked about this

00:44:27.080 --> 00:44:28.770
with the combination
of oxidizing

00:44:28.770 --> 00:44:32.570
and a reducing gas, and
context to eliminate

00:44:32.570 --> 00:44:36.550
these false positive mechanisms.

00:44:36.550 --> 00:44:39.650
And in addition to this,
because most of these mechanisms

00:44:39.650 --> 00:44:43.310
rely on the UV of the
host star, we really

00:44:43.310 --> 00:44:48.670
need to use real UV
data in our modeling.

00:44:48.670 --> 00:44:52.120
In particular, because of
the complex magnetic fields,

00:44:52.120 --> 00:44:56.870
we can't yet predict what
that would be around a star,

00:44:56.870 --> 00:44:58.520
so we rely on
these observations.

00:44:58.520 --> 00:45:01.060
So work is being done
on that as we speak.

00:45:01.060 --> 00:45:04.310
So here is the real data
instead of the cartoon,

00:45:04.310 --> 00:45:07.080
where you have this is
a bright young flaring

00:45:07.080 --> 00:45:09.490
star, AB Leo in the black line.

00:45:09.490 --> 00:45:15.780
And this green line is
typically quiet M star,

00:45:15.780 --> 00:45:19.180
and then the red line is, again,
that lower theoretical limit.

00:45:19.180 --> 00:45:23.640
And we yet don't know how
low can this go, so to speak.

00:45:23.640 --> 00:45:26.110
And this difference is
10 orders of magnitude.

00:45:26.110 --> 00:45:30.280
So understanding what the
lower floor of the UV is

00:45:30.280 --> 00:45:33.060
is going to be really important
for us, especially since we

00:45:33.060 --> 00:45:38.200
only have one UV telescope that
can make those measurement,

00:45:38.200 --> 00:45:39.530
which is Hubble right now.

00:45:39.530 --> 00:45:42.180
And Hubble's not going
to last forever .

00:45:42.180 --> 00:45:44.890
So when we look at
these M star models,

00:45:44.890 --> 00:45:47.740
these are for all the
different types of M stars,

00:45:47.740 --> 00:45:50.080
going from the hotter M
stars to the cooler M stars.

00:45:50.080 --> 00:45:52.080
The only thing I want you
to take away from this

00:45:52.080 --> 00:45:53.750
here is this is
on a linear scale,

00:45:53.750 --> 00:45:56.820
and this shaded
region is the UV part.

00:45:56.820 --> 00:46:00.080
So it doesn't seem like it's
a large part of the flux,

00:46:00.080 --> 00:46:02.340
but it's absolutely
dominating what's

00:46:02.340 --> 00:46:03.930
happening in the atmosphere.

00:46:03.930 --> 00:46:05.860
Because all of
your photochemistry

00:46:05.860 --> 00:46:10.370
only cares about
the UV light that

00:46:10.370 --> 00:46:13.760
has enough energy to
break apart these bonds.

00:46:13.760 --> 00:46:19.900
So if we compare two extremes,
like most maximum amount of UV

00:46:19.900 --> 00:46:22.810
that we would expect and the
most, absolute minimum, maybe

00:46:22.810 --> 00:46:25.560
even less than we would expect
for an Earth like planet

00:46:25.560 --> 00:46:29.250
orbiting an M5 star, you
can see that the spectrum

00:46:29.250 --> 00:46:30.650
might look very different.

00:46:30.650 --> 00:46:34.310
So this is the same planet just
put around two different stars.

00:46:34.310 --> 00:46:37.310
So with different UV, it's
the exact same stellar type.

00:46:37.310 --> 00:46:40.630
It's the same size
and otherwise star,

00:46:40.630 --> 00:46:42.400
except for just different UV.

00:46:42.400 --> 00:46:47.220
And so on the black line,
you have flaring, young star,

00:46:47.220 --> 00:46:50.870
and and in the red line you
have this theoretical minimum.

00:46:50.870 --> 00:46:54.150
And different sorts of gases
build up in the atmosphere

00:46:54.150 --> 00:46:56.320
and create different
features, and you could

00:46:56.320 --> 00:46:58.330
have a very different spectra.

00:46:58.330 --> 00:47:01.040
Which is why characterizing
the UV of these stars

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:02.990
is going to be vital
for us to interpret

00:47:02.990 --> 00:47:06.450
the signs of biosignatures,
and understanding

00:47:06.450 --> 00:47:10.390
the context of what we're
observing in the future.

00:47:10.390 --> 00:47:13.520
So I hope I've convinced
you that stellar matters,

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:17.820
and that UV matters, and for
the second part of my talk,

00:47:17.820 --> 00:47:20.860
I want to talk about
how planets change.

00:47:20.860 --> 00:47:24.290
So we know that planets evolve
through geology, through plate

00:47:24.290 --> 00:47:27.200
tectonics, through
life, and we've

00:47:27.200 --> 00:47:29.830
on Earth had many different
phases going from the Hadean--

00:47:29.830 --> 00:47:34.785
Hell, as I promised I would talk
to you about-- to the Archean,

00:47:34.785 --> 00:47:38.100
to Snowball Earths, and
even Jurassic period.

00:47:38.100 --> 00:47:41.030
Our planet has gone
through many changes.

00:47:41.030 --> 00:47:44.700
And I like thinking
about the history of life

00:47:44.700 --> 00:47:47.690
on our planet to
understand the scale.

00:47:47.690 --> 00:47:50.690
It's really hard for us to
wrap our head around the scale

00:47:50.690 --> 00:47:52.380
of these timelines.

00:47:52.380 --> 00:47:56.310
So I'm going to present it as if
the whole history of our planet

00:47:56.310 --> 00:47:57.900
was in one hour.

00:47:57.900 --> 00:48:01.130
So we started at zero minutes
with the formation of Earth,

00:48:01.130 --> 00:48:04.160
so that was 4.6 billion
years ago or so.

00:48:04.160 --> 00:48:06.480
Then you have the
origin of life.

00:48:06.480 --> 00:48:08.820
We don't exactly know when,
there's a big question

00:48:08.820 --> 00:48:09.430
mark there.

00:48:09.430 --> 00:48:13.110
But somewhere around 3.9
to 4.4 billion years ago.

00:48:13.110 --> 00:48:16.020
That's roughly nine
minutes into the hour.

00:48:16.020 --> 00:48:18.290
Then you have the
oldest signs of life,

00:48:18.290 --> 00:48:21.490
that's around 3.5 to 3.8,
depending on which papers you

00:48:21.490 --> 00:48:23.750
believe, billion
years ago, around

00:48:23.750 --> 00:48:26.670
14 minutes into the hour.

00:48:26.670 --> 00:48:28.420
You have oxygenic
photosynthesis,

00:48:28.420 --> 00:48:33.140
definitely has been around since
around 2.7 billion years ago.

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:36.410
That's 25 minutes into the hour.

00:48:36.410 --> 00:48:39.000
But this always blows my mind
every time I think about this.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:43.020
Multicellular life, so anything
more than just one cell,

00:48:43.020 --> 00:48:45.660
wasn't around until
one billion years ago.

00:48:45.660 --> 00:48:46.300
Very recent.

00:48:46.300 --> 00:48:48.280
That's 47 minutes into the hour.

00:48:48.280 --> 00:48:52.420
And land plants weren't around
until 0.5 billion years ago,

00:48:52.420 --> 00:48:55.400
or 53 minutes into the hour.

00:48:55.400 --> 00:48:58.340
Humans, anatomically modern
humans, not hominids,

00:48:58.340 --> 00:49:01.380
but humans, in our
anatomical form

00:49:01.380 --> 00:49:04.360
have been around
250,000 years ago.

00:49:04.360 --> 00:49:09.914
So that's literally in the
last second of this timeline.

00:49:09.914 --> 00:49:11.330
And the atmosphere,
of course, has

00:49:11.330 --> 00:49:13.300
changed through all of this.

00:49:13.300 --> 00:49:17.580
So here we have
no units, notice,

00:49:17.580 --> 00:49:19.790
because we have very
poor constraints

00:49:19.790 --> 00:49:21.380
on the early atmosphere.

00:49:21.380 --> 00:49:24.860
But the time, this is Earth's
formation all the way up

00:49:24.860 --> 00:49:28.300
to present, and just kind of a
cartoon of what we might think

00:49:28.300 --> 00:49:28.890
has happened.

00:49:28.890 --> 00:49:31.440
So we expect there was
more carbon dioxide

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:34.780
right after the planet
formed, and before oxygen

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:39.310
took hold there was methane as
methanogens kind of dominated

00:49:39.310 --> 00:49:40.780
the planet.

00:49:40.780 --> 00:49:43.190
But then once the
oxygen rose, the methane

00:49:43.190 --> 00:49:45.560
started declining, because
again, those react together

00:49:45.560 --> 00:49:47.380
and the lifetime of
methane goes down

00:49:47.380 --> 00:49:50.160
from being 1,000
years to 10 years.

00:49:50.160 --> 00:49:52.340
Once you have oxygen around,
and then carbon dioxide

00:49:52.340 --> 00:49:53.840
is decreased, and
now of course it's

00:49:53.840 --> 00:49:55.890
increasing again due
to human activity.

00:49:55.890 --> 00:49:59.290
So that's sort of what
we have going on here.

00:49:59.290 --> 00:50:02.770
And oxygen has rose kind of in
two distinct little steps here,

00:50:02.770 --> 00:50:07.940
and there's been some other
complexities along the way.

00:50:07.940 --> 00:50:10.090
But that's the broad picture.

00:50:10.090 --> 00:50:13.040
And so I'm going to take a
look at sort of four time

00:50:13.040 --> 00:50:15.683
points in this Earth history.

00:50:15.683 --> 00:50:19.200
From something that's a
pre-life sort of planet,

00:50:19.200 --> 00:50:22.960
something that has no
necess-- just geological gases

00:50:22.960 --> 00:50:27.730
in the atmosphere, to
something with 1% PAL.

00:50:27.730 --> 00:50:30.750
So, this is Present
Atmosphere Level.

00:50:30.750 --> 00:50:36.540
So that means 1% is 1%
of our 21% of oxygen,

00:50:36.540 --> 00:50:39.510
not 1% of oxygen.

00:50:39.510 --> 00:50:43.000
And then likewise,
10% PAL of oxygen

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.330
would be 2.1% percent
oxygen in the atmosphere

00:50:45.330 --> 00:50:48.300
at 0.8 billion years ago,
and then the modern Earth.

00:50:48.300 --> 00:50:50.940
So those are four time points.

00:50:50.940 --> 00:50:54.320
And this is where we get a
little bit into some graphs.

00:50:54.320 --> 00:50:58.190
We have four slides, of a lot
of lines and a lot of graphs,

00:50:58.190 --> 00:51:02.020
and then we'll get back to
some of the big picture stuff.

00:51:02.020 --> 00:51:10.030
So here is the pre-life
