01:12:43.160 --> 01:12:44.687
Because from
earth's perspective,

01:12:44.687 --> 01:12:46.520
it's going to be right
in front of the star,

01:12:46.520 --> 01:12:49.420
and obviously the star is
billions of times brighter.

01:12:49.420 --> 01:12:51.246
So how can you tell
like that you're

01:12:51.246 --> 01:12:52.620
getting a spectrum
of the planet,

01:12:52.620 --> 01:12:54.020
and not the start behind it?

01:12:54.020 --> 01:12:55.900
-It's a very good
question, because it's

01:12:55.900 --> 01:12:58.970
a bit like you're getting
10 billion photons,

01:12:58.970 --> 01:13:01.427
and then you get one
photon from the planet.

01:13:01.427 --> 01:13:02.760
That's a very difficult problem.

01:13:02.760 --> 01:13:05.093
And when we're talking about
gravitational waves and all

01:13:05.093 --> 01:13:07.442
these other very
difficult measurements,

01:13:07.442 --> 01:13:08.900
this is why it's
difficult. This is

01:13:08.900 --> 01:13:11.620
why it's like looking for a
firefly in front of spotlight

01:13:11.620 --> 01:13:14.840
across the continent.

01:13:14.840 --> 01:13:18.360
So there's a couple different
ways, really shortly, two ways.

01:13:18.360 --> 01:13:22.580
One is you take a picture
when the planet's in front,

01:13:22.580 --> 01:13:24.705
you take it when it's
behind, you subtract the two,

01:13:24.705 --> 01:13:27.840
and you're left behind
with the starlight.

01:13:27.840 --> 01:13:30.490
You look at the light going
through the upper layers

01:13:30.490 --> 01:13:32.810
of the atmosphere as
it's in transmission.

01:13:32.810 --> 01:13:36.360
And you can measure
how it appears

01:13:36.360 --> 01:13:39.052
to change at different
wavelengths due to that.

01:13:39.052 --> 01:13:41.260
